<DOC><DOCNO> AP880411-0275 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-11-88 1448EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Manville-Storage     04-11 0203</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Manville-Storage,0212</SECOND><HEAD>Manville Opens Storage Center for Asbestos-Related Documents</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The pile of documents involving years ofasbestos-related suits against Manville Corp. has grown so large,it needs its own warehouse.   The company announced Monday that it began operation of astorage plant for the paperwork _ 16 million documents in all.   The warehouse operation in Englewood is available to thoseinvolved in resolving asbestos health claims against the company.It was established in cooperation with the Manville Personal InjurySettlement Trust, the committees representing asbestos healthclaimants and other interested parties.   The trust was established under the Manville bankruptcy plan ofreorganization to settle asbestos health claims against the company.   The former asbestos maker filed for protection from itscreditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws on Aug. 26,1982. The bankruptcy court for the Southern District of New Yorkconfirmed the company's plan of reorganization on Dec. 22, 1986.   The company sought bankruptcy protection because of thousands oflawsuits pending by victims of asbestos, which causes asbestosis,an often-fatal lung disease. The victims are seeking billions ofdollars, and future claims are expected to develop.   Experts testified that the claims totaled more than thecompany's entire worth.</TEXT></DOC>